6"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "5-", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 834, "end": 836}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HT1", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.5863604545593262, "span": {"begin": 836, "end": 839}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3356"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "5-HT2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9422601461410522, "span": {"begin": 840, "end": 845}}, {"id": ["mesh:D017371"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "8-OH-DPAT", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9990841150283813, "span": {"begin": 869, "end": 878}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3350"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "5-HT1a", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9883930087089539, "span": {"begin": 883, "end": 889}}, {"id": ["mesh:C014896"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MK212", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9885216951370239, "span": {"begin": 943, "end": 948}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "5", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.5834946632385254, "span": {"begin": 953, "end": 954}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3358"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "5-HT2c", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9938206076622009, "span": {"begin": 953, "end": 959}}, {"id": ["mesh:C502777"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "WAY 161503", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992873668670654, "span": {"begin": 1013, "end": 1023}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "5", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.5848743915557861, "span": {"begin": 1028, "end": 1029}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3358"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "5-HT2c", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9946025013923645, "span": {"begin": 1028, "end": 1034}}], "text": "Given the difficulty in measuring neurotransmitter activity in living organisms, and established activation of serotonin receptors by serotonin, often the relationship between increased levels of serotonin and increased simulation of serotonin receptors is assumed, and focus placed on downstream effects of activation of serotonin pathways and/or behavior effects, with more extensive study in laboratory mammals than fish (see Ramsteijn et al. 2020 for review of mammal studies). &nbsp;Empirical mammal studies show additional support for the mechanism of stimulation of brain 5-HT1a, 5-HT2c receptors leading to inhibition of feeding because of the evolutionarily and functionally conserved pathways modulated by the neurotransmitter serotonin.&nbsp;&nbsp;Use of antagonist compounds to block serotonin receptors (methysergide for 5-HT1/5-HT2 in Ortega et al. 2013, 8-OH-DPAT for 5-HT1a in Perez-Maceira et al. 2014 and Perez-Maceria 2016; MK212 for 5-HT2c in Perez-Maceira et al. 2014 and Perez-Maceria 2016; WAY 161503 for 5-HT2c in Perez-Maceria 2016) have been used to study behavioral effects on feeding.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:17:47 +0000 2026"}